  "bodyHtml": "ORIGINAL\n\nHenri Bergson on why our world is built of objects and space\n\n<p>Immanuel Kant believed that spatiality lies at the bedrock of our understanding of the world, as we have an intuitive sense of space but no ability to detect it in the absence of objects within it. Thus, on top of this sense of space, all other facets of understanding must inevitably be built. In his landmark work <em>Creative Evolution</em> (1907), the French philosopher Henri Bergson diverges from Kant, arguing that our intellect evolved in tandem with our sense of space, with the ability to understand the world in terms of discrete phenomena separated by space helping us to survive. In this experimental short for Epoché Magazine, the Australian writer and composer John C Brady pairs excerpts from <em>Creative Evolution</em> with visual motifs that toy with space and a haunting piano score, making for a mesmerising dance of images, music and ideas.</p>\n<p>Video by <a href=\"https://epochemagazine.org/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\">Epoché Magazine</a></p>\n16 March 2026\n\n<a href=\"/videos/henri-bergson-on-why-the-existence-of-things-precedes-their-possibility\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\">\n\n<img alt=\"Visualisation of a double spiral pattern representing Lorenz attractor with a smaller graph inset on the right showing a mathematical plot labelled Z_n-1.\" loading=\"lazy\" decoding=\"async\" src=\"https://images.aeonmedia.co/images/a2bc1572-88e5-420d-b7de-061dbca7453d/henri-bergson-the-possible-and-the-real-landscape-1.jpg?width=3840&amp;quality=75&amp;format=auto\">\n\n<p>videoThinkers and theories</p><p>Henri Bergson on why the existence of things precedes their possibility</p><p>3 minutes</p></a><a href=\"/videos/can-you-see-music-in-this-painting-how-synaesthesia-fuelled-kandinskys-art\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\">\n\n<img alt=\"Abstract painting with geometric shapes, lines and circles in various colours on a beige background.\" loading=\"lazy\" decoding=\"async\" src=\"https://images.aeonmedia.co/images/c7b41c73-e176-4db1-aafe-5db1a89373c0/the-sound-of-colour-landscape-2.jpg?width=3840&amp;quality=75&amp;format=auto\">\n\n<p>videoBeauty and aesthetics</p><p>Can you see music in this painting? How synaesthesia fuelled Kandinsky’s art</p><p>10 minutes</p></a><a href=\"/videos/simple-entities-in-universal-harmony-leibnizs-evocative-perspective-on-reality\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\">\n\n<img alt=\"Close-up microscopic view of Diatom plankton with transparent, geometric shapes connected by thin, radiant lines, set against a dark background.\" loading=\"lazy\" decoding=\"async\" src=\"https://images.aeonmedia.co/images/df93e1c2-8efe-4e18-96a2-d82b08cd3477/leibniz-the-monadology-landscape-3.jpg?width=3840&amp;quality=75&amp;format=auto\">\n\n<p>videoMetaphysics</p><p>Simple entities in universal harmony – Leibniz’s evocative perspective on reality</p><p>4 minutes</p></a><a href=\"/videos/i-am-therefore-i-think-how-heidegger-radically-reframed-being\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\">\n\n<img alt=\"Photo of a musician in a hat playing a double bass with a microphone in front, set against a dark background.\" loading=\"lazy\" decoding=\"async\" src=\"https://images.aeonmedia.co/images/9397a716-f235-4bdb-b36a-54bdf155ba31/being-in-the-world-from-plato-to-heidegger-landscape-1.jpg?width=3840&amp;quality=75&amp;format=auto\">\n\n<p>videoHistory of ideas</p><p>I am, therefore I think – how Heidegger radically reframed being</p><p>13 minutes</p></a><a href=\"/videos/time-is-fundamental-space-is-emergent-why-physicists-are-rethinking-reality\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\">\n\n<img alt=\"A man with glasses and a beard speaking, wearing a dark jacket and grey collar, with a blurred globe in the background.\" loading=\"lazy\" decoding=\"async\" src=\"https://images.aeonmedia.co/images/ab9f37c1-e0af-4f6f-a4c1-f363e1fd4fab/lee-smolin-time-and-space-landscape-2.jpg?width=3840&amp;quality=75&amp;format=auto\">\n\n<p>videoPhysics</p><p>Time is fundamental, space is emergent – why physicists are rethinking reality</p><p>9 minutes</p></a><a href=\"/videos/is-it-more-likely-youre-a-person-with-a-past-or-an-ephemeral-brain-in-a-void\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\">\n\n<img alt=\"A collage of various objects, animals, and clothes surrounding a large brain illustration on a black background.\" loading=\"lazy\" decoding=\"async\" src=\"https://images.aeonmedia.co/images/affc1078-c19d-4b79-bfca-1eb392c63632/the-boltzmann-brain-paradox-landscape-2.jpg?width=3840&amp;quality=75&amp;format=auto\">\n\n<p>videoLogic and probability</p><p>Is it more likely you’re a person with a past, or an ephemeral brain in a void?</p><p>6 minutes</p></a>\n\n<a href=\"/videos/background-music-was-the-radical-invention-of-a-trailblazing-composer\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\">\n\n<img alt=\"Black and white photo of a man with glasses and a beard, resting his chin on his hand, wearing a suit.\" loading=\"lazy\" decoding=\"async\" src=\"https://images.aeonmedia.co/images/822b132e-d72a-4f07-9407-3cd4ab64c33c/saties-furniture-music-landscape-1.jpg?width=3840&amp;quality=75&amp;format=auto\">\n\n<p>videoArt</p><p>Background music was the radical invention of a trailblazing composer</p><p>17 minutes</p></a><a href=\"/videos/aristotle-was-wrong-and-so-are-we-there-are-far-more-than-five-senses\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\">\n\nORIGINAL<img alt=\"Watercolour painting of a man holding a glass of red wine, with text “IN SIGHT Barry C. Smith” on a greenish background.\" loading=\"lazy\" decoding=\"async\" src=\"https://images.aeonmedia.co/images/c2ecad5f-858e-4270-b3da-f415f2e22ed0/barry-c-smith-main-v2.jpg?width=3840&amp;quality=75&amp;format=auto\">\n\n<p>videoNeuroscience</p><p>Aristotle was wrong and so are we: there are far more than five senses</p><p>6 minutes</p></a><a href=\"/videos/on-the-beholders-share-how-past-experience-influences-our-perception-of-art\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\">\n\n<img alt=\"Painting of a person with pink hair in a pink frame, flanked by smaller framed paintings of a ship and unicorn, blue wall background.\" loading=\"lazy\" decoding=\"async\" src=\"https://images.aeonmedia.co/images/62181519-839f-4243-adab-6498a32b90d8/neuroscience-of-perception-v2.jpg?width=3840&amp;quality=75&amp;format=auto\">\n\n<p>videoNeuroscience</p><p>On the ‘beholder’s share’ – how past experience influences our perception of art</p><p>5 minutes</p></a>"
